<font color="#FF0000">COMMENTS TO JOHN</font><br>
<tt>Tue Sep 16 20:40:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John,<br><br>
Cook makes good points. I have been on this site since last fall, and the intensity of emotive conduct has not altered, though the contributors have somewhat.<br><br>
This site cycles. It seems to alternate between rational discussion of politics, things that hurt, GI humor, and frenzied lashing out. Such is the way of war, too. <br><br>
It is important for everyone to realize that the Vietnam Veterans on this site, for the most part, stratify and connect themselves into a mirage 'Nam combat unit, and what you see written here reflects that association. This is nothing unusual, because many Vietnam Veterans associate this way in public and private life. For many, it is a matter of simple emotional survival, and for others it is a way of bringing forth, discussing, and dealing with issues of intense pain with those in whom they can place complete trust. Many here are very vulnerable, or have you forgotten?<br><br>
It is also important that everyone to realize that the Vietnam Veteran has the burden of not only dealing with the historical and political issues that must be processed and understood for the Vietnam Veteran to anchor in time and space, but also dealing with the fallout realities of the actual conflict. It is, therefore, not realistic to expect any Vietnam Veteran to be completely cold, analytical, academic, and objectively disconnected in ways acceptable to those who are more comfortable with a sterile world.<br><br>
This is a site of real people discussing real events and real problems. There is acting out at many psychological levels. There are conflicts and disagreement, attacks and counterattacks. Guilt, shame, pride, anger, and countless states in between are all here for the world to see.<br><br>
The education for those who did not experience the Vietnam War is this site taken in total. It is a reflection of the War. It reflects in some ways all wars. War is not nice. That is the truth behind it all.<br><br>
It is better for the truth to be seen, than sanitized, packaged, and regurgitated to satisfy an artificial reality which avoids plucking an internal chord that many would rather deny in themselves, than face head on.<br><br>
Two final notes.<br><br>
1. What is this society going to do to heal the Vietnam Veteran damaged by the war? Probably nothing but complain or hide.<br><br>
2. PBS television airs far more controversial and foul languaged programming than anyone will ever see on this site. The persuit of truth is never gothic sterility.        <br><br>
Art
